										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>It&#8217;s December, and so the literary internet, such as it is, is awash in best-of book lists. I cannot say that this website is not <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-38-favorite-books-of-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">complicit</a> in this (are we the worst? we might be the worst), but it can also, admittedly, get a little tedious. After all, books are not only important during the year of their publication, and you never know when you&#8217;ll pick up something old, weird, and randomly incredible. To that end, I asked the Lit Hub staff about the best books they read in 2024 that were <em>not</em> published this year. The result is a list of recommendations for anytime, or whenever you need something a little different.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811223034" class="external" target="_blank"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246762" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/9780586055847-us/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us.jpg" data-orig-size="316,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Muriel Spark, Loitering With Intent (1981)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us-190x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246762 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us-190x300.jpg" alt="Muriel Spark, Loitering With Intent (1981)" width="190" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us-190x300.jpg 190w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us-38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780586055847-us.jpg 316w" sizes="(max-width: 190px) 100vw, 190px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Muriel Spark, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811223034" class="external" target="_blank">Loitering With Intent</a> (1981)</strong></h2>
<p>A Scottish woman stole my heart this year. But we all love Muriel Spark, right? Who can do more in two hundred pages? Who can reliably dazzle and mystify without ever seeming to show off?</p>
<p><em>Loitering With IntentÂ </em>is a totally bananas novel. Like the Nunez, it&#8217;s also concerned with the ethics of authorship, butâ€”you know, make it funny. A young woman on the precipice of realizing her own literary goals falls in with a group of eccentric richies who are all looking to ghost-write their memoirs. What follows is a meditation on the folly of narrativizing oneâ€™s own life. When does the story eat the truth? Thereâ€™s some door-slamming farce and hallucinatory set-pieces on the way to answering this question, but we always stay grounded. Just extreme fun. <em>â€“Brittany K. Allen, Staff Writer</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781620407226" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246763" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/31131700640/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640.jpg" data-orig-size="1140,1928" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Barbara Trapido,Â Brother of the More Famous JackÂ (1982)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-177x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-605x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246763 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-177x300.jpg" alt="Barbara Trapido,Â Brother of the More Famous JackÂ (1982)" width="177" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-177x300.jpg 177w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-605x1024.jpg 605w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-768x1299.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-35x60.jpg 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-908x1536.jpg 908w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640-30x50.jpg 30w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/31131700640.jpg 1140w" sizes="(max-width: 177px) 100vw, 177px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Barbara Trapido,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781620407226" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Brother of the More Famous Jack</em></a>Â (1982)</strong></h2>
<p>I cannot get over this charmer from a woman who â€œ<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/may/22/featuresreviews.guardianreview26" class="external" target="_blank">became a novelist late and by accident.</a>â€ Originally published in 1982, Trapidoâ€™s debut is a bildungsroman with freckles of first love. The book follows Katherine, a plucky British university student, as she falls in succession for an eccentric professor, his mighty wife, their charismatic family, and some other surprise dudes. Our open-hearted hero is determined to suck up life experience. She chronicles her swoons, heartbreaks, and quickening consciousness at a fond remove. And against its chosen backdrops of swinginâ€™ 60s London, Oxford, and Rome, the prose just shimmers. A little like Lynn Barberâ€™sÂ <a href="https://granta.com/an-education/" class="external" target="_blank"><em>An Education</em></a>â€”but even better company. Thanks to my friendly booksellers atÂ <a href="http://threelives.com/" class="external" target="_blank">Three Lives Books</a> for nudging this one onto my pile. <em>â€“BA</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679767954" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="98460" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/when-your-imposter-syndrome-is-out-of-control/heartburn-nora-ephron/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron.jpg" data-orig-size="261,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Heartburn &#8211; Nora Ephron" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-98460" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron-196x300.jpg" alt="" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Heartburn-Nora-Ephron.jpg 261w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></a></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h2><strong>Nora Ephron, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679767954" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Heartburn</em></a> (1983)</strong></h2>
<p>Poor Rachel Samstat; at seven months pregnant she discovers that her husband, Mark, is in love with another woman. Thereâ€™s not much plot to the novel other than Rachel coping with her failing marriage, debating whether to try and win Mark back or throw him outâ€”the reader bounces around to her group therapy sessions, friendships, and career opportunities, enjoying a handful of eighties recipes (pot roast made with a can of cream and mushroom soup, a truly odious sounding casserole made with pears and lima beans) sprinkled throughout. But the driving force here, and for all Ephron, is voiceâ€”she is funny and <em>fun</em>. There are certainly less politically correct moments, but nothing so wildly offensive that itâ€™s unreadable, especially since Rachel (who is just a stand-in for Ephron and her separation from Carl Bernstein) is incredibly self-deprecating; she holds the harshest criticism for herself. <em>â€“Emily Firetog, Deputy Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811234696" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="222310" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-12-best-book-covers-of-june-3/71ryhr7ha0l/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L.jpg" data-orig-size="773,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="My Search for Warren Harding" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-660x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-222310" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-193x300.jpg" alt="My Search for Warren Harding" width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-193x300.jpg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-660x1024.jpg 660w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-768x1192.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/71RyHr7Ha0L.jpg 773w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Robert Plunket,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811234696" class="external" target="_blank"><em>My Search For Warren Harding</em></a>Â (1983)</strong></h2>
<p>This is a genuinely funny novel, which is not something I get to say often when recommending a book. The characters in Plunketâ€™s book are bizarre and bumbling, and they get themselves into untenable situationsâ€”itâ€™s a literary treatment of the kind of comedy I&#8217;m more used to seeing on the screen. The punchlines and targets of the humor are dated in places and really donâ€™t hold up in others, but I was surprised overall at how much the jokes still work. It&#8217;s refreshing, especially when so much of the humor I come across in novels is either too smartâ€”arch, MFA-workshopped references and clever asidesâ€”or else itâ€™s too perkyâ€”sunny, rom-com bubbliness filtered through Twitter memes and Tumblr lingo. Plunketâ€™s novel is neither of those things. Heâ€™s biting and satiricalâ€”thereâ€™s a mean edge to this book. More than from the characters and set-ups, the tone comes from Plunketâ€™s narrator, who is a preening ghoul, a delusional man who crashes through the world judging everyone but himself. Heâ€™s cruel, but funny and unfiltered, the kind of person you want to be seated next to at a boring dinner party. â€“<em>James Folta, Staff Writer</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780394725802" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246764" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/9780394725802/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802.jpg" data-orig-size="257,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Phyllis Rose, Parallel Lives (1983)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246764 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802-193x300.jpg" alt="Phyllis Rose, Parallel Lives (1983)" width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802-193x300.jpg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9780394725802.jpg 257w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Phyllis Rose, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780394725802" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Parallel Lives</em></a> (1983)</strong></h2>
<p>We are in an era of marriage and divorce books aplenty: it feels like every month there is a new, buzzy, burn-it-all-down manifesto about our culture and that institution. Some are amazing, some are terrible, but if you have to read just one book about marriage, an end-all-be-all book, it should be <em>Parallel Lives</em> by Phyllis Rose. Rose is straightforward about her topic, and clear about her directions as you read the book: it should make you question the presumption of marriage, or as she calls it, the <em>fiction</em> of marriage. She uses the writings of five Victorian literary couples to delve deeply into the inner workings of their unions, to understand their patterns, sex lives, power balances, and general happinesses, while consistently returning to the idea of marriage as a whole, and how central that story has been to all of our lives whether we know it or not. She makes fascinating and radical demands for â€œmore plotsâ€ to take up the same level of importance weâ€™ve long allotted to marriage, and to open our minds to allow different sorts of imaginative realities to make up our lives rather than the one we have been fed from the beginning. A must read! <em>â€“Julia Hass, Book Marks Assistant Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250326690" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246789" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/9781250326690/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690.jpg" data-orig-size="1613,2475" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="9781250326690" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-667x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246789 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-196x300.jpg" alt="" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-667x1024.jpg 667w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-1001x1536.jpg 1001w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-1335x2048.jpg 1335w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781250326690.jpg 1613w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></a></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;