<h2>Cameron Reed (writing as Raphael Carter), <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250326690" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Fortunate Fall </em></a>(1996)</h2>
<p>I love a good reissues series and Tor&#8217;s &#8216;Essentials&#8217; line is one of the best going. Sometimes, they&#8217;re reissuing well-known titans of the genre (Gene Wolfe, China MiÃ©ville, Kim Stanley Robinson)â€”but sometimes, they&#8217;re bringing back into print a novel that has otherwise disappeared from the conversation when it really shouldn&#8217;t have. <em>The Fortunate Fall</em> is a great example of the latter: a gripping late-90s cyberpunk novel in conversation with William Gibson and Neal Stephenson but also <em>The Continuous Katherine Mortenhoe</em> andÂ <em>Flow My Tears, The Policeman Said</em> (and maybe a smidge of <em>Star Trek IV</em>, IYKYK). It&#8217;s set some ~200 years into the future, where augmented humans deliver the news (and all of what they feel along with it) and Africa is the technological center of the worldâ€”but it is a powerfully timely story (like all great SF) about genocide, queer love, surveillance, revolution, and the dangers of giving over our humanity in the pursuit of more advanced technology. Here&#8217;s hoping this book gets a well-deserved and more robust second life. â€“<em>Drew Broussard, Podcasts Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781784786625" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246765" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="424,650" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Mike Davis, Late Victorian Holocausts: El NiÃ±o Famines and the Making of the Third World (2000)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246765 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy-196x300.jpg" alt="Mike Davis, Late Victorian Holocausts: El NiÃ±o Famines and the Making of the Third World (2000)" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/getimage_a3f7ac7b-eead-44df-aa06-808122f2e30b-copy.jpg 424w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Mike Davis, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781784786625" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Late Victorian Holocausts: El NiÃ±o Famines and the Making of the Third World</em></a> (2000)</strong></h2>
<p>This is the second book I&#8217;ve read from Mike Davis (<em>City of Quartz</em>, a prescient history of the military-prison-industrial complex in Los Angeles, was frequently passed around by my anarchist friends just after college) and <em>Late Victorian Holocausts</em> may be even more prophetic and revelatory. First published in 2000, <em>Late Victorian Holocausts</em> looks at the deadly combination of drought, colonialism, and imperialism at the end of the 19th century, in which the seeds of catastrophe can be found in the repeated failures of imperial overlords to prevent enormous numbers of their new subjects from starving to death. While the specific climate conditions examined in the text are linked to the El Nino/la Nina cycle, the book clearly sets out the mechanisms of extraction &amp; indifference that are already part of the enormous suffering caused by climate change; suffering that will surely continue to make this book distressingly relevant to our current age.</p>
<p>One particularly damning fact: while the British claimed that building railroads in India would allow them to move grain surpluses quickly to famine-stricken areas, the opposite proved trueâ€”the British colonial administrators took grain reserves away from starving people, and those in areas connected to imperial infrastructure were thus more likely to die of famine than those without a local railway connection. Another damning fact: the British government censored the one guy to respond appropriately to a famine so much that the next time a big drought came around, he showed exceptional cruelty in quest of avoiding further criticism. The number of deaths caused by the modernization of poverty, the indifference of imperial infrastructure, and the extreme vacillations of climate conditions is proven by Mike Davis to have been enormousâ€”and the factors that caused so much suffering are back in play for the conceivable future. This book is not a warningâ€”we&#8217;ve come too far for that. It is a prophecy. <em>â€“Molly Odintz, CrimeReads Managing Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/for-rouenna-sigrid-nunez/1102992453" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246767" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/41nf7kehtpl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="655,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sigrid Nunez, For Rouenna (2001)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246767 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" alt="Sigrid Nunez, For Rouenna (2001)" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41NF7KEHTPL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 655w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></a></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></d