<h2><strong>Sigrid Nunez, <a href="https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/for-rouenna-sigrid-nunez/1102992453" class="external" target="_blank"><em>For Rouenna</em></a> (2001)</strong></h2>
<p>Last year I decided to become a Nunez completist. Thereâ€™s just something so confident and hypnotic about her booksâ€”she has a knack for drawing you into anotherâ€™s mind and holding you hostage there. This earlier work follows a novelist, fresh off the heels of a successful debut, who gets re-entangled with a childhood acquaintance who served as an army nurse in Vietnam. The anonymized writer protagonist will be familiar to fans of Nunezâ€™s recent fiction (<a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780735219458" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Friend</em></a><em>, </em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593715512" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Vulnerables</em></a>) but Rouenna the nurse is a singular characterâ€”brittle, warm, and haunted by sharp turns. This novel draws a fine psychological portrait of a traumatized veteran, then layers in a complex exploration of emotional and political violence. (Notably, this book is alsoâ€”like my other recc, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781635901863" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Do Everything in the Dark</em></a>, written in the melancholic aftermath of 9/11.) Is our hero right to take on Rouennaâ€™s story, and attempt to capture it in fiction? What do we owe our subjects, anyway? Smart, unsettling, and unafraid to linger on the knots. I read it in one go.Â <em>â€“BA</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780375712920" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246768" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/il_1080xn-3620041223_qeqe-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="1080,1695" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Stephen L. Carter, The Emperor of Ocean Park (2002)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-191x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-652x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246768 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-191x300.jpg" alt="Stephen L. Carter, The Emperor of Ocean Park (2002)" width="191" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-191x300.jpg 191w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-652x1024.jpg 652w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-768x1205.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-979x1536.jpg 979w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/il_1080xN.3620041223_qeqe-copy-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s2