<h2><strong>Stephen L. Carter, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780375712920" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Emperor of Ocean Park</em></a> (2002)</strong></h2>
<p>It&#8217;s been a long time since I read a mystery so thoroughly, thrillingly immersive as Stephen L. Carter&#8217;s <em>The Emperor of Ocean Park</em>. Carter&#8217;s novel chronicles the family dynamics of Talcott Garland in the wake of his father&#8217;s death and offers a vivid portrait of upper class African-American life moving between Washington D.C. and Martha&#8217;s Vineyard. Political scandal and family secrets inform the novel&#8217;s action, but more than anything it&#8217;s the lens of our narrator, viewing the evolution of American society and intellectual discourse, that makes The Emperor of Ocean Park such an unforgettable novel. <em>â€“Dwyer Murphy, CrimeReads Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781635901863" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246769" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/220765/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765.jpg" data-orig-size="306,475" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="gary indiana do everything in the dark" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-246769" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765-193x300.jpg" alt="gary indiana do everything in the dark" width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765-193x300.jpg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/220765.jpg 306w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Gary Indiana,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781635901863" class="external" target="_blank">Do Everything in the Dark</a></em>Â (2003)</strong></h2>
<p>I had this book languishing in my TBR pile for a long time, I think because Gary Indianaâ€™s prose was so often presented to me with daunting adjectives. (<em>Acidic, acerbic, caustic, sharp&#8230;</em>) The wait was foolish; I regret it. Though certain of those adjectives do apply to this chronicle of an artistic friend group fractured by premature AIDS deaths, heartbreaks, petty and profound jealousies, and inevitable middle-age drift, this novel can also be (brutally) funny, and its audacious conveying of the unruliest emotions totally won me over. Unlike many of his peers, the late, great Indiana never romanticized the New York demi-monde. But that only renders the pain and pleasures of this specific community all the more alive. Also, the sentences! Snacks, every one! <em>â€“BA</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h2><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250784018" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="101527" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/midwestern-women-an-essential-reading-list/gilead-marilynne-robinson/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2100" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Gilead &#8211; Marilynne Robinson" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-101527" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson.jpg 1400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Marilynne Robinson, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250784018" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Gilead</em></a> (2004)</strong></h2>
<p>Sometimes you end up avoiding books because they are just too damn bigâ€”spiritually, not necessarily literally (although sometimes that too). Despite my now-wife gifting me a copy of <em>Gilead</em> on our first serious Christmas together as a couple, nearly a decade ago, and despite my otherwise-strongly-held plan to divest of any books that sit on my TBR for longer than three yearsâ€¦ I hung onto this one, until just a couple days ago. I picked it up before dawn on a brutally cold, lightly snowy morningâ€¦ and it turns out, it absolutely lives up to the hype. Unbelievably good prose, Iâ€™m so mad it took me this long to get around to it. As a life-long avowed atheist-existentialist, I wonder if I was worried about the religiosity of Robinsonâ€™s writingâ€”but, if youâ€™ll indulge me a riff on a quote from this very novel: â€œRobinson is a famous Calvinist, but she is about as good on the joyful aspects of life as anybody, and she loves the world. Of course she thinks religion is a necessary means of understanding the world and joy cannot exist pure and undisguised. That is her one error, and it is significant. But she is marvelous on the subject of joy, and also on its religious expressions.â€ <em>â€“DB</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780767923095" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246770" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/41y8auhdjfl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="652,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Tina Brown,Â The Diana ChroniclesÂ (2007)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246770 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg" alt="Tina Brown,Â The Diana ChroniclesÂ (2007)" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/41y8AuHdJFL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 652w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Tina Brown,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780767923095" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Diana Chronicles</a>Â </em>(2007)</strong></h2>
<p>When I&#8217;m doing one of the myriad mundane tasks that make up most of a life (chores, errands, exercise, pushing a stroller), all I want is a stream of smart, barbed gossip in my ears. All the better if it&#8217;s gossip of yore, read by Tina Brown. If you have a similar craving, I highly recommend Brown&#8217;s snarky, well-researched tale of Princess Diana&#8217;s life and death, as well as the general dysfunction of the Windsors. Few had Brown&#8217;s access, and fewer can tell a story as compellingly as she can. At the risk of sounding like a much-loathed British tabloid, it&#8217;s delicious. <em>â€“Jessie Gaynor, Senior Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780767923095" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="89956" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/14-great-books-that-would-make-terrible-movies/2666-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666.jpg" data-orig-size="243,375" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2666" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-89956" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666-194x300.jpg" alt="2666" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/2666.jpg 243w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Roberto BolaÃ±o, tr. Natasha Wimmer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780312429218" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>2666</em></a> (2008)</strong></h2>
<p>I put off reading <em>2666</em> for years. It was too big, too daunting, too death-haunted. It sat there at the bottom of my TBR pile, sandwiched between <em>Lonesome Dove</em> and <em>Infinite Jest</em>, mocking me. People told me wild, impossible things about it. They said there was an entire section dedicated to a book critic love triangle. They talked in hushed tones about the endless, hellish descent that made up the femicide portion of the book. They said it was the most significant literary work of the 21st century. They said a great many things, and I was afraid. But they were right. This gargantuan meditation on violence and literature is horrific, comic, playful, deadening, thrilling, and existentially terrifying. I have no idea how long it took me to get through it, but I emerged from its bloody pages changed. Carpel tunneled, and changed. <em>â€“Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor-in-Chief</em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345497529" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="16119" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/interview-with-a-bookstore-porter-square-books/515jmuwjs8l/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/515jMUwjS8L.jpg" data-orig-size="334,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The City and the City by China Mieville" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/515jMUwjS8L-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/515jMUwjS8L.jpg" class="alignc