<h2><b>Daniel Woodrell, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316133654" class="external" target="_blank"><i>The Bayou Trilogy</i></a> (2011)</b></h2>
<p>Every year, when â€œsweater weatherâ€ begins to lose its charm and the sun starts to set at 4pm, I try to read my way to hotter climes. This yearâ€™s destination was northern Louisiana as I ventured into Daniel Woodrellâ€™s sweaty, profane, damn-near Rabelaisian trio of hardboiled Cajun novellas. Set in the fictional upriver bayou town of St. Bruno, the trilogy follows reluctant hero Detective RenÃ© Shade as he navigates life among the crooks, hoodlums and ne&#8217;er do wells whoâ€™ve set up shop at the edge of the swamp, busting crooked cops, fist-fighting with family members, and generally trying to do the right thing. Woodrell has a virtuosic ear for argot-heavy dialogue and has a talent for evoking all of lifeâ€™s wonderful intoxicants in a way that can leave one a little woozy after reading. Best of all, the trilogy is not so much procedural as it is deeply atmospheric, which is a good thing on cold northern nights. <em>â€“Jonny Diamond, Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250050458" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="89565" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/30-of-the-worst-couples-in-literature/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p.jpg" data-orig-size="611,920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-89565" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p-199x300.jpg" alt="love affairs of nathaniel p book cover" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/love-affairs-of-nathaniel-p.jpg 611w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Adelle Waldman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250050458" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Love Affairs of Nathaniel P</em></a> (2013)</strong></h2>
<p>This is the kind of book that makes me mad at everyone whoâ€™s read it for not having told me about it until now. Just that perfect sweet spot genre: literary, funny, smart, chilling in its astuteness, realistic and humane, the kind that makes me fall in love with books all over again for their staggering ability to convey life as it feels. If it was a wine it would be drinkable: goes down easy and youâ€™re always wishing for more. <em>Love Affairs</em> sums up dating and men and desire in a scathing and yet unfortunately accurate way, depicting the quests and the longings and the voracious need to be wanted, and yet the harrowing insistence of the void at the center of these wants. The realization that one may never quite get what theyâ€™re looking for, may always be seeking. Itâ€™s eviscerating about men, but lives inside the mind of one with crystalline authenticity: you may not like what you find there, but you have to respect Adelle Waldmanâ€™s ability to access the egotistical millennial male mind and its contrasting, confused, and at times cruel notions. <em>â€“JH</em></p>
