<h2><strong>David Graeber, <a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/220295/the-democracy-project-by-david-graeber/" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Democracy Project </em></a>(2013)</strong></h2>
<p>As the American democratic experiment lurches towards obsolescence I returned to David Graeberâ€™s post-game analysis of Occupy Wall Street (of which he was something like a co-founder). Equal parts on-the-ground history and anarchist organizing playbook, <i>The Democracy Project</i> uses the OWS movement as a jumping off point to examine the rich, weird, and truly innovative history of direct democracy in America. If we are going to get through the next four years and, more importantly, help those most at risk from actively hostile national politics, weâ€™re going to need all the good ideas we can get; I wish Graeber were still around to help, but at least he left us his incredible body of work. <em>â€“JD</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781609807870" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="124508" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-memoirs-of-the-decade/ernaux_theyears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020.jpg" data-orig-size="500,741" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Annie Ernaux, tr. Alison L. Strayer, The Years (2017)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020-202x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-124508" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020-202x300.jpg" alt="Annie Ernaux, tr. Alison L. Strayer, The Years (2017)" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Ernaux_TheYears-f_feature-254f966c53579197e74e9a7e1731d020.jpg 500w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Annie Ernaux, tr. Alison Strayer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781609807870" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><i>The Years</i></a> (2017) </strong></h2>
<p>I may be the last person I know to readÂ <em>The Years</em>, and I can&#8217;t say whyâ€”it is exactly the kind of book I like best: genre-bending, discursive and variable, at once a story of a single consciousness and the story of the whole world. Originally published in France in 2008,Â <em>The Years</em> is a memoirâ€”of sortsâ€”of the author&#8217;s life from 1940 to 2006, but it is also a book about a generation, a book about all of our generations, a book about time itself. It was, weirdly, just what I needed during a cold, hard winter. <em>â€“Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781804294529" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="102247" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/paradise-rot/paradise-rot-jenny-hval/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval.jpg" data-orig-size="260,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Paradise Rot &#8211; Jenny Hval" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-102247" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval-195x300.jpg" alt="" width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Paradise-Rot-Jenny-Hval.jpg 260w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Jenny Hval, tr. Marjam Idriss, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781804294529" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Paradise Rot</a></em> (2018)</strong></h2>
<p>I love a nasty little freak book, and <em>Paradise Rot</em> is nothing if not a nasty little freak book for freaks. The basic plot of the book is that a young woman from Norway studies abroad in England and lives in a weird warehouse-turned-apartment with a weird roommate. The real plot of this book is the concept and reality of decay. The apartment is falling apart, sprouting mold and fungus in every room, and the two roommates only exacerbate the rot. The main character, Jo, has become untethered in her new home and sheâ€™s starting to go to seed.</p>
<p>I loved how visceral and gross Hval/Idrissâ€™ descriptions were. The book sometimes felt like a series of prose poems rather than a novella, which is a vibe I always love. The writing is lucid and precise even as the world of the book becomes more and more dreamlike. <em>Paradise Rot</em> is a book that sticks with you. Itâ€™s also very much a piss book. Impossible to accurately capture how much piss is in this book. However much youâ€™re imagining right now, itâ€™s not enough. <em>â€“McKayla Coyle, Publishing Coordinator</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781941250334" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246771" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/version-1-0-0-10/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L.jpg" data-orig-size="1600,2400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kelsey Wroten, Cannonball (2019)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246771 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-200x300.jpg" alt="Kelsey Wroten, Cannonball (2019)" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-1365x2048.jpg 1365w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/81FUW5Wzo8L.jpg 1600w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Kelsey Wroten, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781941250334" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Cannonball</a></em> (2019)</strong></h2>
<p>If youâ€™re a messy art lesbian, youâ€™ll love this book. It follows an aspiring author as she attempts to make the shift from art school graduate to professional artist. <em>Cannonball</em> is, in many ways, a character study. Except the character at its center is wholly unlikeable, which makes the book feel less like an auteur project and more like a really great gossip session where your best friend tells you everything about the worst person they ever met. I donâ€™t know about you, but thatâ€™s my idea of a perfect day. The art is stunning, the story is engaging and funny and frustrating all at once. Itâ€™s relatable without feeling like itâ€™s trying too hard to be relatable (not an easy feat). When my friend Oliver recommended this to me, they described it as â€œif Charles Foster Kane was an art lesbian.â€ If that doesnâ€™t hook you, I donâ€™t know what will. <em>â€“MC</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811229074" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="211807" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/rabih-alameddines-recommends-the-best-short-books-he-read-in-2022/minor-detail-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail.png" data-orig-size="372,602" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="minor detail" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail-185x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail.png" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-211807" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail-185x300.png" alt="" width="185" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail-185x300.png 185w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail-37x60.png 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail-31x50.png 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/minor-detail.png 372w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 185px) 100vw, 185px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Adania Shibli,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811229074*" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Minor Detail</em></a> (2020)</strong></h2>
<p><em>Minor Detail</em>Â is a short book of quiet empathy. Shibliâ€™s novel is split into two parts: a Bedouin-Palestinian girl is assaulted and killed by Israeli soldiers in 1949, and decades later, a modern Palestinian woman tries to uncover more about the crime. Shibli writes beautifully and subtly, and the book is full of disarming turns of phrase. Her contemporary character, driving while considering a modern road map next to a map of pre-Nakba Palestine, worries that she â€œmay get lost in the folds of a sceneâ€ that has changed so drastically.Â <em>Minor Detail</em> is about memory, counter-memory, and the resulting folds of all this layering. And it&#8217;s about what and who gets swallowed in those folds. <em>â€“JF</em><strong>Â </strong></p>
<p><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984898487" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246772" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/9781984898487/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487.jpg" data-orig-size="291,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="revelator" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-246772" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487-194x300.jpg" alt="revelator" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984898487.jpg 291w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Daryl Gregory, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984898487" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Revelator</em></a> (2021)</strong></h2>
<p>Readers I trust have been raving about this for a while, but for whatever reason it just never made it to the top of my TBRâ€”until this October, when it stood out among a pretty stacked spooky-book reading spree. Set in the first half of the century, replete with great backwoods-Gothic visuals and a genuinely original â€˜creatureâ€™ haunting the margins, it manages to be chilling and thrilling in equal measure while never shirking the big emotional weight of a story thatâ€™s also about family and identity. Iâ€™ll be thinking about the Ghostdaddy for a long, long time. <em>â€“DB</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984880390" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246774" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/version-1-0-0-11/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L.jpg" data-orig-size="1725,2550" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Version 1.0.0&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="boyt loved and missed" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-693x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-246774" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-203x300.jpg" alt="boyt loved and missed" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-693x1024.jpg 693w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-768x1135.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-1039x1536.jpg 1039w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-1385x2048.jpg 1385w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/91J0UfxgV5L.jpg 1725w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Susie Boyt, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681377810" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Loved and Missed</a>Â </em>(2021)</strong></h2>
<p>It&#8217;s difficult to write about child-rearing in a way that&#8217;s neither saccharine nor desperate, but Susie Boyt&#8217;s slim, perfect novel about a woman raising the daughter of her own daughter, who is in the grip of addiction, strikes the perfect balance of quotidian joy and profound heartbreak. Describing the novel as a page-turner feels wrong, but in its quiet way, it was more gripping than anything else I&#8217;ve read recently. I&#8217;m in awe of Boyt&#8217;s ability to turn the gathering of flowers or the drinking of tea on the front steps into moments of pure wonder. <em>â€“JG</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984880390" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246773" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/attachment/9781984880390/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390.jpg" data-orig-size="298,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Matthew F. Delmont,Â Half American (2022)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246773 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390-199x300.jpg" alt="Matthew F. Delmont,Â Half American (2022)" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/9781984880390.jpg 298w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Matthew F. Delmont,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984880390" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Half American</em></a> (2022)</strong></h2>
<p><em>Half AmericanÂ </em>collects the varied histories of Black Americans in the 1930s-1940s fight against fascism, from the Spanish Civil War through World War II. The title comes from a provocative letter that a young black man wrote to his newspaper, asking â€œShould I sacrifice my life to live half American?â€ It was an urgent question.</p>
<p>Delmont casts a wide net, telling the stories of soldiers, airmen, writers, and laborers, focusing especially on the unsung military support and supply staff who made victory possible. The book tells of courage in combat, but also courage in labor struggles, on military bases, in the legal system, and in DCâ€™s halls of power. Delmontâ€™s book complicates the rosy narrative America tells itself about WWII â€” as usual in American history, we failed to honor the lofty idealism of our rhetoric with our actions. America won the war, but was unable to deliver the double victory so many Black Americans asked and fought for: a victory against racist fascism abroad, and a victory against racist fascism at home. <em>â€“JF</em><strong>Â </strong></p>
<h2><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250335685" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="246775" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-old-books-we-read-in-2024/71qf79l8s3l-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="668,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sara Flannery Murphy, The Wonder StateÂ (2023)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-246775 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Sara Flannery Murphy, The Wonder StateÂ (2023)" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/71QF79L8S3L._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 668w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Sara Flannery Murphy, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250335685" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Wonder State</em></a>Â (2023)</strong></h2>
<p>One of the hardest things about the end of any given year is rushing to finish books-from-that-year in case you want to include them on your list. Sara Flannery Murphyâ€™s <em>The Wonder State</em> is one such read that I didnâ€™t get to until Januaryâ€”and then I was kind of pissed, because I loved it and wished Iâ€™d gotten to it in time for last yearâ€™s list. It is absolutely terrific, with Stephen King vibes and Kelly Link energy: five old friends drawn back home to the Ozarks by a cryptic letter. They return and, in alternating timelines, discover/rediscover the strange and magical houses that peppered their small town. Tremendously imaginative while keeping up a thrillerâ€™s paceâ€”Iâ€™ve not stopped thinking about these houses for almost a year.Â <em>â€“DB</em></p>
										
																				
																		
